{"badges":["TM5","TM6"],"preparations":[{"content":["Place semolina, rice and 120 g of the coconut milk into mixing bowl and mix <b>20 sec\/speed 5<b>. Transfer into a bowl and set aside to soak for 15 minutes. Clean and dry mixing bowl.","Place yeast and 60 g of the coconut milk into mixing bowl and heat <b>1 min\/37°C\/speed 1<b>.","Add flour, sugar, baking powder, cardamom, remaining 40 g coconut milk and reserved soaked semolina mixture and knead <b>2 min\/<b>. Transfer into a bowl, cover with plastic wrap and set aside to prove for 2 hours (or until doubled in size). Clean and dry mixing bowl.","Place water into mixing bowl and heat <b>5 min\/Varoma\/speed 1<b>. Spray 6 idli moulds, silicone egg poaching moulds or silicone muffin cases with oil. Transfer 1 tablespoon of mixture (approx. 60 g) into each of the prepared moulds. Place moulds into Varoma dish, place Varoma into position, secure Varoma lid and steam <b>12 min\/Varoma\/speed 1<b>. Transfer into thermal serving bowl or other large bowl and cover to keep warm.","Re-spray moulds with oil and distribute remaining idli mixture between moulds. Place moulds into Varoma dish, place Varoma into position, secure Varoma lid and steam <b>12 min\/Varoma\/speed 1<b>. Serve warm."]}],"ingredients":[{"title":"","content":["170 g semolina","50 g cooked rice","220 g coconut milk","1 tsp dried instant yeast","170 g plain flour","80 g sugar (optional)","2 tsp baking powder","½ tsp ground cardamom","700 g water","oil spray, for greasing"]}],"id":"r137259","imageLink":"https:\/\/3.bp.blogspot.com\/-PTwXEwoxV2s\/XZWYrqJG6DI\/AAAAAAAAeB0\/SXkoShPKSv845CFeKCOfiI-uBLuBuioAgCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_Hd6wRJdVEpWA0zEd.png","title":"Rava idli","publishedAt":"2017-07-03T00:00:00Z","nutrition":{"protein":"3.5 g","fat":"3.3 g","uom":"per 1 portions","carbohydrates":"28.5 g","calories":"665 kJ \/ 158 kcal"},"usefulItems":"bowl, plastic wrap, silicone egg poaching moulds or idli moulds, thermal serving bowl or other large bowl","hintsAndTricks":["Traditional idlis are made using fermented lentils and rice and then steamed. The fermention process (which usually takes 12-24 hours) breaks down the starches, making them easier to digest. Our version uses semolina, making the recipe quicker and easier to make.","Idlis are meant to be eaten with a chutney or other flavoursome sauces or spreads, or used to accompany curries. In the southern part of India, idli is often part of a traditional breakfast.","You can serve these warm with butter. We served ours with Sambhar (please refer to the recipe on this recipe chip) and rice."],"basicInfo":["easy","15m","2h 40m","12 portions"]}